		<title>The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus part 1 (part iii)</title>
		<link>http://www.mathemafrica.org/?p=15170</link>
		<comments>http://www.mathemafrica.org/?p=15170#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 11 Jul 2019 09:52:53 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jonathan Shock]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Courses]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[First year]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[MAM1000]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Undergraduate]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[fundamental theorem of calculus]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[MAM1000W]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.mathemafrica.org/?p=15170</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>So, we are now ready to prove the FTC part 1. We&#8217;re going to follow the proof in Stewart and add in some discussion as we go along to motivate what we are doing. What we are going to prove is that:</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p><img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7Bdx%7D+%5Cint_a%5Ex+f%28t%29+dt%3Df%28x%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="&#92;frac{d}{dx} &#92;int_a^x f(t) dt=f(x)" title="&#92;frac{d}{dx} &#92;int_a^x f(t) dt=f(x)" class="latex" /></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>for <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=x%5Cin+%5Ba%2Cb%5D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="x&#92;in [a,b]" title="x&#92;in [a,b]" class="latex" /> when <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=f&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="f" title="f" class="latex" /> is continuous on <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Ba%2Cb%5D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="[a,b]" title="[a,b]" class="latex" />.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>Proof:</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>we define <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=g%28x%29%3D%5Cint_a%5Ex+f%28t%29dt&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="g(x)=&#92;int_a^x f(t)dt" title="g(x)=&#92;int_a^x f(t)dt" class="latex" /> and we want to find the derivative of <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=g&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="g" title="g" class="latex" />. We will do this by using the fundamental definition of the derivative, so let&#8217;s look at calculating this function at <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=x&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="x" title="x" class="latex" /> and <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=x%2Bh&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="x+h" title="x+h" class="latex" /> &#8211; ie. how much does it change when we change <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=x&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="x" title="x" class="latex" /> by a little bit?</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p><img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=g%28x%2Bh%29-g%28x%29%3D%5Cint_a%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29+dt-%5Cint_a%5Ex+f%28t%29+dt&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="g(x+h)-g(x)=&#92;int_a^{x+h}f(t) dt-&#92;int_a^x f(t) dt" title="g(x+h)-g(x)=&#92;int_a^{x+h}f(t) dt-&#92;int_a^x f(t) dt" class="latex" /></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>But remember that the definite integral is just the area, so this difference is the area between a and x+h minus the area between a and x. Which is just the area between x and x+h. Using the properties of integrals, we can write this formally as:</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p><img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=g%28x%2Bh%29-g%28x%29%3D%5Cint_a%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29+dt-%5Cint_a%5Ex+f%28t%29+dt%3D%5Cleft%28%5Cint_a%5E%7Bx%7Df%28t%29%2B%5Cint_x%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29%5Cright%29-%5Cint_a%5E%7Bx%7Df%28t%29%3D%5Cint_x%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29dt&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="g(x+h)-g(x)=&#92;int_a^{x+h}f(t) dt-&#92;int_a^x f(t) dt=&#92;left(&#92;int_a^{x}f(t)+&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)&#92;right)-&#92;int_a^{x}f(t)=&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)dt" title="g(x+h)-g(x)=&#92;int_a^{x+h}f(t) dt-&#92;int_a^x f(t) dt=&#92;left(&#92;int_a^{x}f(t)+&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)&#92;right)-&#92;int_a^{x}f(t)=&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)dt" class="latex" /></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>and we can write, for <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=h%5Cne+0&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="h&#92;ne 0" title="h&#92;ne 0" class="latex" />:</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p><img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cfrac%7Bg%28x%2Bh%29-g%28x%29%7D%7Bh%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bh%7D%5Cint_x%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29dt&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="&#92;frac{g(x+h)-g(x)}{h}=&#92;frac{1}{h}&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)dt" title="&#92;frac{g(x+h)-g(x)}{h}=&#92;frac{1}{h}&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)dt" class="latex" /></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>Restated, we can think of this as the area between x and x+h divided by h.&#8230;</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>So, we are now ready to prove the FTC part 1. We&#8217;re going to follow the proof in Stewart and add in some discussion as we go along to motivate what we are doing. What we are going to prove is that:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7Bdx%7D+%5Cint_a%5Ex+f%28t%29+dt%3Df%28x%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="&#92;frac{d}{dx} &#92;int_a^x f(t) dt=f(x)" title="&#92;frac{d}{dx} &#92;int_a^x f(t) dt=f(x)" class="latex" /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>for <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=x%5Cin+%5Ba%2Cb%5D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="x&#92;in [a,b]" title="x&#92;in [a,b]" class="latex" /> when <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=f&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="f" title="f" class="latex" /> is continuous on <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Ba%2Cb%5D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="[a,b]" title="[a,b]" class="latex" />.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Proof:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>we define <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=g%28x%29%3D%5Cint_a%5Ex+f%28t%29dt&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="g(x)=&#92;int_a^x f(t)dt" title="g(x)=&#92;int_a^x f(t)dt" class="latex" /> and we want to find the derivative of <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=g&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="g" title="g" class="latex" />. We will do this by using the fundamental definition of the derivative, so let&#8217;s look at calculating this function at <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=x&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="x" title="x" class="latex" /> and <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=x%2Bh&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="x+h" title="x+h" class="latex" /> &#8211; ie. how much does it change when we change <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=x&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="x" title="x" class="latex" /> by a little bit?</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=g%28x%2Bh%29-g%28x%29%3D%5Cint_a%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29+dt-%5Cint_a%5Ex+f%28t%29+dt&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="g(x+h)-g(x)=&#92;int_a^{x+h}f(t) dt-&#92;int_a^x f(t) dt" title="g(x+h)-g(x)=&#92;int_a^{x+h}f(t) dt-&#92;int_a^x f(t) dt" class="latex" /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>But remember that the definite integral is just the area, so this difference is the area between a and x+h minus the area between a and x. Which is just the area between x and x+h. Using the properties of integrals, we can write this formally as:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=g%28x%2Bh%29-g%28x%29%3D%5Cint_a%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29+dt-%5Cint_a%5Ex+f%28t%29+dt%3D%5Cleft%28%5Cint_a%5E%7Bx%7Df%28t%29%2B%5Cint_x%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29%5Cright%29-%5Cint_a%5E%7Bx%7Df%28t%29%3D%5Cint_x%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29dt&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="g(x+h)-g(x)=&#92;int_a^{x+h}f(t) dt-&#92;int_a^x f(t) dt=&#92;left(&#92;int_a^{x}f(t)+&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)&#92;right)-&#92;int_a^{x}f(t)=&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)dt" title="g(x+h)-g(x)=&#92;int_a^{x+h}f(t) dt-&#92;int_a^x f(t) dt=&#92;left(&#92;int_a^{x}f(t)+&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)&#92;right)-&#92;int_a^{x}f(t)=&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)dt" class="latex" /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>and we can write, for <img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=h%5Cne+0&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="h&#92;ne 0" title="h&#92;ne 0" class="latex" />:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img src="//s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cfrac%7Bg%28x%2Bh%29-g%28x%29%7D%7Bh%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bh%7D%5Cint_x%5E%7Bx%2Bh%7Df%28t%29dt&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0" alt="&#92;frac{g(x+h)-g(x)}{h}=&#92;frac{1}{h}&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)dt" title="&#92;frac{g(x+h)-g(x)}{h}=&#92;frac{1}{h}&#92;int_x^{x+h}f(t)dt" class="latex" /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Restated, we can think of this as the area between x and x+h divided by h.&hellip;</p>]]></content:encoded>
